{{other people||Fred Allen (disambiguation)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Use British English|date=April 2016}} {{infobox football biography | name = Fred Allen | image = | fullname = Frederick Allen | height = | position = [[Outside right]] | birth_date = July 1860 | birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England | death_date = c. {{death year and age|1926|1860}} | death_place = Birmingham, England | years1 = – | clubs1 = Springhill Methodists | caps1 = | goals1 = | years2 = 1890–1892 | clubs2 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]] | caps2 = 3 | goals2 = 0 <!-- | years3 = 1892–1895 | clubs3 = [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] | caps3 = 6 | goals3 = 2 --> }}
'''Frederick Allen''' (July 1860 – c. 1926) was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played in the [[Football Alliance]] for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]].
Allen was born in the [[Hockley, Birmingham|Hockley]] district of [[Birmingham]] and played football for Springhill Methodists before joining Small Heath in 1890.<ref name=Matthews68>{{cite book |author=Matthews, Tony |title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record |year=1995 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |page=68 |isbn=978-1-85983-010-9}}</ref> He played three times for them in the Football Alliance in the [[1891–92 in English football|1891–92 season]] when [[Jack Hallam (footballer)|Jack Hallam]] was switched to a more central forward position.<ref>Matthews, p. 141.</ref> He died in Birmingham in about 1926.<ref name=Matthews68/>
A forward called Fred Allen is recorded to have played for [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] from 1892 to 1895. He was the club's top goalscorer during the 1893–94 season.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Definitive Luton Town F.C. |publisher=Soccerdata |author=Bailey, Steve |date=December 1997 |page=89 |isbn=1-899468-10-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Luton Town Story 1885–1985 |publisher=Luton Town F.C. |author=Collings, Timothy |year=1985 |page=309 |isbn=0-951067-90-7}}</ref>
